Instructions

For your assignment, you will be writing code to recreate these plots (they aren’t necessarily the most beautiful, but they will teach different plotting skills!). Please use the provided hw3_template.R R script template in the class RStudio Cloud Workspace. Do NOT submit a script that does not use this template! Read all instructions carefully to ensure your own success. Following the instructions is half the battle of doing well.

Specific Instructions:

  1. For each question, you should write code to recreate the plot. Save the plot to a variable and print that variable with print(). The purpose of this instruction is to make you practice saving plots to variables!

  2. Your code must be spaced out onto separate lines as we have learned in class. There will be deductions for plotting code that is all on one line. The purpose of this instruction is to force you build this organizational habit as early as possible.

  3. When recreating the plots, you do not need to specifically recreate:
    • Specific colors and fills that I use. If I use “just a color” or “just a fill”, you can use any color/fill you want, as long as you are specifying the same type of feature.
    • Exact point or line size

  4. When recreating the plots, you do need to make sure you focus on:
    • Matching axes labels and plot titles
    • Matching the geom used and its styling
    • The specific aesthetic mappings
    • The plot theme. For all plots, one of the following themes is used. You can see what the themes look like here.
      • theme_classic()
      • theme_minimal()
      • theme_bw()
      • theme_gray() (This is the default theme. If the plot uses this theme, you do NOT need to code it - it’s the default!)

  5. Ensure your code contains comments!! Specifically, any line of code that you do not immediately and like muscle-memory understand should have a comment. This helps you to develop the skill and understand what your own code does.
    • Please note: Many beginners feel “stupid” writing comments. Sometimes they think, “If I were good at coding, I wouldn’t need comments. Comments make me look like I’m not smart enough to code.” This is a fundamental (but normal!) misunderstanding! The best coders are the ones who make their code as easy as possible to read and re-use. Using comments is a sign that you are a STRONG PROGRAMMER who knows how to write clear code. Not using comments is a sign that you enjoy pain and you love to forget what your code does 30 seconds after you wrote it.

  6. Don’t make this harder than it has to be. Every type of plot you have to make on this homework was introduced in lecture and/or the ggplot2 interactive exercises. Unless the question explicitly teaches you new code, you have see the code you need to use before.

  7. Really helpful tip: While doing the homework, you may notice your plots are a different overall size than mine. In fact, when viewing plots in R, the size of the plot is exactly determined by the size of the “Plots” window. Just make it bigger or smaller to see your plot at a different size. There is also a button “Zoom” you can click to see it larger in another window (you may need to tell you browser’s pop-up blocker to allow it).

Additional tips for success:

  • You will not receive any credit for answers without corresponding code that produces those answers.
  • Make sure your code runs WITHOUT an errors before submitting. DO NOT SKIP THIS STEP! Ensuring code runs without errors is MORE IMPORTANT than writing code in the first place.
    • If there are errors in your code, you should comment out the code so that it does not actually run. This is BETTER than allowing buggy code to run - it shows me you attempted the code, but understood that it didn’t work properly. If you leave buggy code in the script without commenting it out, there will be deductions.
  • As always, you are encouraged to work together and use the class Slack to help each other out, but you must submit YOUR OWN CODE.

Plot 3


HintS:

  • Make sure your order of variables agrees with this plot!! You will need to use the function fct_relevel() (and you may need to use it again on the HW too). Also be sure that your legend ends up named the same as mine (see the exercises!).
  • Notice that both distributons are visible even though they are overlapping. Make sure yours are too!
  • This plot places the legend at the bottom of the plot. This is actually a modification to the plot’s theme. Because ggplot plots are just added components on top of one another, you will need to change the legend position AFTER you set its theme (think about why this MUST BE THE CASE, and experiment with it!). The legend can be re-positioned by adding on the following code: theme(legend.position = "bottom"). To learn more (but not to submit for this questoin!), see what happens if you use “top”, “left”, or “right” instead of “bottom”.

Plot 6


HintS:

  • See the black point with small lines in each distribution? This represents the mean and standard error (SE) of each distribution. In this case, the standard errors are very small, so the lines are a bit tricky to see, but they are there! These points are conveniently, amazingly, and automatically added with the plot component, stat_summary(). This is a special ggplot2 function which can easily add a summary statistic onto a plot. No arguments are necessary because by default, it plots mean and SE.
  • It will reveal a warning message: “No summary function supplied, defaulting to mean_se(),” which means you used it CORRECTLY!!!!
  • You will see the black point is larger than the other points. You should also make sure your plot has these relative sizes, but the exact numbers can differ from mine.
  • You will want to use the argument width with your geom. Your value does not need to exactly match mine, but it should definitely differ from the default.
